abstracts.cdata!:
More than 70 percent of
            Timor-Leste's health facilities were destroyed or badly
            damaged in the violence and conflict that followed the
            referendum on independence from Indonesia in 1999. Around 80
            percent of the country's health managers left the
            country as did all but around 20 doctors. In this context of
            devastation, the first health sector rehabilitation project
            aimed to build health institutions and develop a policy
            framework for a new health system, while providing basic
            health services. The basic service delivery system had two
            key features: to work with NGOs to deliver health services
            while the system was being built, and to start the process
            of district planning to build capacity and lay the
            foundations for inter-government relations and institutional
            linkages. The second project started a hospital
            restructuring program while continuing the activities begun
            under the first.

repnme.cdata!:
Timor-Leste - Health Sector Rehabilitation
            and Development Project

abstracts.cdata!:
Project ratings are as follows: Project
            outcome is satisfactory; sustainability is likely;
            institutional development impact is substantial; Bank
            performance is satisfactory; and Borrower performance is
            satisfactory. This project has significant lessons for
            fragile and post-conflict environments including the need
            for donors to adopt a Sector-wide approach in a low capacity
            environment and a phased approached to health sector
            development. Other lessons comprised supporting policy
            development from the start;  early mapping of health
            facilities and assessment of construction and rehabilitation
            needs; adopting a transitional strategy; linking the
            establishment of government structures and procedures to
            longer term investment programs; and the importance of
            documenting post-conflict reconstruction of health systems.

repnme.cdata!:
East Timor - Health Rehabilitation and
            Development Project

abstracts.cdata!:
The Health Sector Rehabilitation and
            Development Program Project for East Timor aims to
            immediately address basic health needs of the population of
            East Timor and develop policies and a suitable health
            system. There are two main project components. The first
            component restores access to basic health services and
            focuses on accelerated delivery of selected high priority
            programs (immunizations, TB, nutrition, health promotion)
            and service providers at the district level to provide a
            basic package of services. The transitional strategy also
            supports temporary repairs, some new building, and
            re-equipment. It re-establishes an administrative
            infrastructure and provides training for service delivery,
            management, and administration. It also prepares an action
            plan for excess hospital capacity. A major part of this
            component involves establishing pharmaceuticals/logistics
            systems. It will promote stakeholder participation through
            various consultation schemes. The second component addresses
            medium to long-term issues. Through capacity building,
            studies, and stakeholder consultations, it begins the
            process of defining and developing health policies
            appropriate to the country. It also supports a strategy for
            human resource development, technical assistance, and
            regulations for pharmaceuticals.
